Ha.... I'm going 'all in'..... not exactly cautious but when I looked at the numbers and compared it to venom on my first forecast 90 - 110k was the figure that stood out for a DC / warnerBros release with a break-out solo villain character. Reviews have been either great or scathing.... and when I see 5 star reviews pitted against 2 star reviews that question the moral integrity and value of the film I just see publicity. Comic book fans will want to see it regardless..... the more discerning movie-goer will be intrigued by the Oscar buzz and conflicting reviews. The upshot is that I think it'll out do Venom and then more some.... tipping it into the territory I've chosen. Warner Bros see this as the first in a potential series of break out films so will be (have been) keen to promote... so we're looking at a 4000 plus theatre release to get it off to a healthy start..... $80k plus with the rest of the week bringing in enough to put it over the $90k mark.

Many people know Joker from the Dark Knight, which scored an opening weekend did $158mm gross (source: BO Mojo). Note that the question asks about opening WEEK and not WEEKEND. So we must estimate weekend as % of week to get to our answer. You can get this data from BO Mojo - weekends are about 75% of the total usually, so to normalize we must divide by 0.75. Dark Knight then was likely ~$210mm first week.

Unconventional anti-hero back story makes it harder to predict, but the darker plot line seems to be getting lots of publicity and is perhaps appropriate for the times. I am guessing towards the lower end based on the less clear market it should appeal to.

Using data from Box Office Mojo, Director Todd Phillips average gross opening earnings (adjusted for ticket price inflation) is $39.6M. Actor Joaquin Phoenix average gross opening earnings (adjusted for ticket price inflation) is $29.33M. Based on these statistics, I would initially forecast an opening week of less than $70M.

Statistically, not all DC comic movies have performed as well in their opening week as perhaps Marvel movies. However, DC movies featuring Batman or more villians (such as suicide squad) have performed well in the opening week. Both the director/writer and main star average less than 70,000,000 their opening week, but â€˜the Jokerâ€™ trailer has received over 1 million hits in the first hour of its release.
I base this on historical numbers from Warner Brother Films and the Batman franchise.
The Dark Knight's opening weekend domestic gross - $158,411,483. Suicide Squad opening weekend domestic gross - $133,682,248.
Comparing opening box office for batman and wonder woman, as well as knowledge in its reviews and hype.

Comparative films of the genre have consistently grossed over $130M (ex. Dark Knight 2008 -$158M, Dark Knight Rises 2012- $160M) coupled with the earning successes of the Avengers series public appetite for superhero-themed movies may act as a multiplier for the Joker's box office gross. (films featuring Joaquin Pheonix grossed on average at the box office around $7M in 2018, but this likely isn't an effective way of gauging the earning potential of the Joker as Pheonix stars in a number of obscure and sometimes short films likely not intended for national audiences.) Other possible indicators of the earning potentials of the film include pre-release awards, which as of September 7th include the Venice Film Festival's Golden Lion award (the last major American film to receive the award was the Shape of Water, which grossed $192M at the box office.
I used DC films and other R-rated films as a base rate along with forecasts from Box Office Mojo.

A really interesting film to try and predict ..... prediction based on an awful lot of competing factors but generally based around Warner Bros need to launch this as the first in a franchised sub-genre. They are still smarting from the Ben Affleck batman disaster so need to roll out a success despite this being a relatively low budget movie. Hence It's being pushed at Venice and Toronto festivals and is likely to get a 4000+ cinema domestic release which is likely to take it to around the 70k mark in first weekend alone. Rest of the week should push it over 90k..... as long as current critical mood about the film continues.

Even though I would not see this flick, I try to follow what popular enthusiasms tell me about our culture. I understand why other DC/Marvel Universe films have done as well as they have. Joaquin Phoenix is a talented actor, but the target audience for this movie is interested in characters, not the performers. Very few will go see Mr. Phoenix if they are not interested in the character. The Joker character is at this point a stranded asset. The film will probably make its costs back, but will under-perform the expectations (and certainly the hopes) of its producers.

Having read peoples input below and done a little digging I have to say that... Based on what I've looked up, the economy has very little impact on cinema/theatre attendance. Peoples opinions and political views don't stop them from going to watch a movie and spin off prequel stories such as Rogue one (which I would tentatively compare the joker to) capture peoples attention and interest. What impacts box office takings though are BFFC ratings (or whatever the equivalent is in the US) with a 15 in the UK (and equivalent elsewhere) I'd expect the joker to take a 25-30% hit in comparison to such movies. The number of explosions in the trailers are lacking which means your typical "End game" fans will show less interest. But I still expect this to take over 130 mil. I'm not going to hazard at exactly how much and I might revise my prediction after some more analysis, but right now I find it hard to see this movie taking less than 145 mil.
